{{About|features within the Arctic Ocean|a Canadian marine ecozone|Arctic Basin Marine Ecozone (CEC)}}
{{more footnotes|date=August 2013}}
[[File:Arctic Ocean bathymetric features.png|thumb|350px|Main [[bathymetry|bathymetric]] features of the [[Arctic Ocean]]]]
The '''Arctic Basin''' (also '''North Polar Basin''') is an [[oceanic basin]] in the [[Arctic Ocean]], consisting of two main parts separated by the [[Lomonosov Ridge]], a [[mid-ocean ridge]] running between north [[Greenland]] and the [[New Siberian Islands]]. The basin is bordered by the [[continental shelves]] of [[Eurasia]] and [[North America]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Seebohm|first=Henry|title=The North Polar basin|year=Reviews 1894|publisher=Annual report of the Board of Regents of the Smithsonian Institution|location=Washington|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=chi.086719742}}</ref>
<ref>{{cite web|title=North Polar Basin|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/419363/North-Polar-Basin|work=Encyclopædia Britannica|accessdate=27 September 2012}}</ref>
* The '''[[Eurasian Basin]]''' (also '''Norwegian Basin''') consists of the [[Nansen Basin]] (formerly: Fram Basin) and the [[Amundsen Basin]]
* The '''[[Amerasian Basin]]''' consists of the [[Canada Basin]] and the [[Makarov Basin]]

==History==
There was an expedition to the North Polar Basin by [[Fridtjof Nansen]] and [[Otto Sverdrup]] in the ''[[Fram]]'' [[Nansen's Fram expedition|in 1893–1896]]. [[Roald Amundsen]] sailed across the North Polar Basin between 1922 and 1924.

